@Eric Nunya Fair warning, this is going to be long, but I think you need to hear this.

"Well. I was misinformed then, and owe Alex Jones yet another apology.

At this point, I should just assume everything I've heard Alex Jones say that was crazy was clipped out of context in some way."

Well, by his own admission. . . he's kind of retarded. But yes, if you want to understand Alex Jones, or anyone really, it pays to engage with their larger body of work, because even 'in-context' clips can be misconstrued if you don't understand their larger body of work. One my favorite examples of this is Nietzsche's 'God is dead' famous quote. it's hard to blame Christians, for example, for misunderstanding that and vilifying Nietzsche for saying that, when atheists took it and ran with it first, also misunderstanding what he said. Sure, knowing the full quote helps, what was most holy has bled to death under our knives, what sacred games will we have to invent, blah blah blah so on and so forth, but things really come into focus only after reading several of his books and understanding that Nietzsche believed many things that were directly in line with what I would describe as 'source-doctrine' for Christianity, with a primary focus on the notion that "For our light affliction, which is but for a moment, is working for us a far more exceeding and eternal weight of glory," a sentiment which seemed to guide his every thought and argument. Nietzsche believed that all pain and suffering was ultimately not to be shunned, but cherished as precious gifts the same as the 'good' parts of life, and even that full quote takes on new meaning in that light. In other words, Nietzsche didn't believe that the 'problem of evil' went away if you took God out of the equation. It only gave unsatisfied people someone to blame. The real problem, was viewing parts of life as 'evil' to begin with, and that he believed, would destroy the world, made clear when he said, "The Christian resolution to see the world as ugly and bad is _making_ the world ugly and bad." People who are like lightning rods, or as Nietzsche would put it, a lit stick of dynamite, are magnets for that kind of misunderstanding.

"And, yeah, I consider actually religious people to be... mentally disconnected from reality, let's say."

Or mistaken about reality. 'Disconnected' is not the word I would use.

"Actually believing the metaphysics to be literally true makes you think you're immune to snake bites."

Not necessarily. It depends on the particulars of those metaphysics. I'm not saying people like that aren't out there, but a lot of people like that, depend on spurious reasoning even when appealing to their own sources. Since we're using snake handlers as an example, this is a common belief in certain branches of Pentecostal churches, mainly in the Appalachia region of America. They source their argument from a passage in the gospel of Mark, essentially an assurance that should they be put under threat of certain things, they won't be harmed, and probably point to the apostle Paul's experience getting bitten by a snake and not dying, later on the in the New Testament.

Now, I'm going to be honest; I've seen and been a part of things I do not have the capacity to explain given my current knowledge of natural science, so I'm not even going to begin to make claims like 'this is a miracle' or anything like that. I will simply describe something that happened to me once and you can decide for yourself what you think about it. Back when I was much younger, I was in a building with a bunch of other young people, most of whom were ostensibly Christian, and the reason for my use of the qualifier will become clear shortly. We didn't _do_ ecstatic mystic experiences. We were all normal, buttoned-down, anti-holy-roller, 'normal' Christians. On a whim, a lot of us decided we'd stick around after service, just to hang out and talk for a bit, so we went to the top floor of the building to get out of everyone's way. None of us had anything weird to eat or drink, drugs weren't pumped into the air, nobody had any kind of agenda, there wasn't even any church leadership involved in this. Well, out of nowhere, as we were just hanging out, chilling, and talking, we were all struck with the same extreme hallucination at once. The building's top broke open, something like an angelic-looking being descended, and we all heard it speak. Apparently, I only found this out later, there was an earthquake that occurred at that time, which would explain why we all heard the windows rattling like they were getting ready to break.

@Eric Nunya At the time, this was all very new to me, so I randomly cracked open my fresh new bible and went straight to the book of Acts, straight to the story where the apostles, and I quote, "ascended to the upper room of the building," and were filled with tongues of fire and, to use their verbiage, "received the holy spirit." I read that, thought to myself, 'yeah, this sounds like that.' There were many other things that happened after that, most of which I can't reproduce or replicate, but what was most interesting to me, as that most of us had a reaction resembling 'holy shit it's all real.' There were children of the church leadership that were there, and for some strange reason, they did their best to try to flat-out cover that event up. People who talked about it, got aggressively shushed, then shunned, and ultimately driven out. There were only a few people there that were sympathetic, but one thing that was common, one of those things that happened after that, was that any time I talked with the people involved about anything related to the biblical text, none of us needed to reference anything, and we each knew what the other was talking about, even things I hadn't read yet. That probably isn't very clear; I mean we all functionally had perfect recall of the biblical text, no matter how obscure the passage, and whenever one of us was about to make a point about the relevant passage in question, someone else would stop them and make their exact point for them. Anyone who wasn't part of that event, save for a few, found that very, very unnerving and told us so, and it wasn't long before my former friends and I had that experience, started denying it had happened, publicly. In private, they still acknowledged what we all saw, what we all heard, but they started denying that they had had that experience when around anyone who wasn't part of it. I never denied it, but I stopped even mentioning it at all some years ago, until now.

No, I didn't record it. No, I'm not going to pretend I know how to summon angels or any other weird shit like that. No, I _definitely_ can't replicate it, no I'm not trying to convert you into believing anything (In fact, if by some dark twist of fate I discover that you decided to adopt some kind of weird belief system because you heard this story, I'm going to be extremely unhappy, one reason I don't talk about this hardly ever, please, do not make me responsible for that), no I am not even going to begin to pretend to know why or how that happened. The _entire_ reason I told you all of this, is to make the point that it is _easy_ to fall into thinking, or believing, a certain way because of particular experiences, due to the pattern-recognition mechanisms our psychology has evolved, and that having experienced something does not equate to any real understanding of the thing experienced.
